Bartholin's Cyst
A Bartholin's cyst is a fluid-filled sac that forms on a Bartholin's gland. Bartholin's glands are small glands in the folds of skin near the opening of the vagina (labia). This type of cyst causes a bulge or lump near the opening of the vagina.
If you have a cyst that is small and not infected, you may be able to take care of it at home. If your cyst gets infected, it may cause pain and your doctor may need to drain it.
What are the causes?
This condition may be caused by a blocked Bartholin's gland. Germs (bacteria) inside of the cyst can cause an infection.
What are the signs or symptoms?
• A bulge or lump near the opening of the vagina.
• Discomfort or pain.
• Redness, swelling, or fluid draining from the area.
How is this treated?
You may not need treatment if your cyst is not causing symptoms. The cyst can go away on its own with home care. Home care includes hot baths or heat therapy.
Large cysts or cysts that are infected may be treated with:
• Antibiotic medicine.
• A procedure to drain the fluid.
Cysts that keep coming back will need to be drained many times. Your doctor may talk to you about surgery to remove the cyst.
Follow these instructions at home:
Medicines
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor.
• If you were prescribed an antibiotic medicine, take it as told by your doctor. Do not stop taking it even if you start to feel better.
Managing pain and swelling
• Try sitz baths to help with pain and swelling. A sitz bath is a warm water bath in which the water only comes up to your hips and should cover your buttocks. You may take sitz baths a few times a day.
• If told, put heat on the affected area as often as needed. Use the heat source that your doctor recommends, such as a moist heat pack or a heating pad.
◦ Place a towel between your skin and the heat source.
◦ Leave the heat on for 20–30 minutes.
◦ Take off the heat if your skin turns bright red. This is very important. If you cannot feel pain, heat, or cold, you have a greater risk of getting burned.
General instructions
• If your cyst was drained:
◦ Follow instructions from your doctor about how to take care of your wound.
◦ Use feminine pads to absorb any fluid.
• Do not push on or squeeze your cyst.
• Do not have sex until the cyst has gone away or your wound from drainage has healed.
• Take these steps to help prevent a cyst from returning, and to prevent other cysts from forming:
◦ Take a bath or shower once a day. Clean the area around your vagina with mild soap and water when you bathe.
◦ Practice safe sex to prevent STIs. Talk with your doctor about how to prevent STIs and which forms of birth control to use.
• Keep all follow-up visits.
Contact a doctor if:
• You have a fever.
• You get more redness, swelling, or pain around your cyst.
• You have fluid, blood, pus, or a bad smell coming from your cyst.
• You have a cyst that gets larger or a cyst that comes back.
Summary
• A Bartholin's cyst is a fluid-filled sac that forms on a Bartholin's gland. These small glands are found in the folds of skin near the opening of the vagina (labia).
• This type of cyst causes a bulge or lump near the opening of the vagina.
• Try sitz baths a few times a day to help with pain and swelling.
• Do not push on or squeeze your cyst.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.
